WHEREAS, the Nebraska Public Power District purchased two hundred two
acres of farmland for more than five million dollars from the Nebraska Public
Power District's Land Management Manager, who is responsible for the land
purchase and the Chief Audit and Ethics Officer; and
WHEREAS, neither the Land Management Manager nor the Chief Audit and
Ethics Office filed a conflict-of-interest statement as of May 16, 2025; and
WHEREAS, section 49-1499.03 requires that an employee of a political
subdivision identify potential conflicts if the salary and benefits of the
employee exceed one hundred fifty thousand dollars and if the employee would be
required to take any action that would cause financial benefit or detriment to
him or her; and
WHEREAS, the Chief Audit and Ethics Officer made more than two hundred
fifty thousand dollars in 2024; and
WHEREAS, the substantive discussion by the Nebraska Public Power
District's Board of Directors regarding the purchase took place in an executive
session, closed to the general public; and
WHEREAS, an appraisal conducted by the Nebraska Public Power District
priced the fair market value of the land at eleven thousand dollars per acre,
approximately two million three hundred thousand dollars total, but the final
purchase price was set at twenty-five thousand dollars per acre, just over five
million dollars total; and
WHEREAS, the difference of two million seven hundred thousand dollars will
be paid by Nebraska ratepayers; and
WHEREAS, Nebraska Public Power District's Chief Executive Officer stated
"As I look back at this particular transaction and how it was approached, I
